<title>JAPAN: Goldman strategist bullish on stocks allocation.</title>
<headline>Goldman strategist bullish on stocks allocation.</headline>
<dateline>TOKYO 1997-03-04</dateline>
<text>
<p>Jeffrey Weingarten, a Goldman Sachs International global strategist, said on Tuesday that the brokerage recommends allocating a greater proportion of funds to equities than bonds over the next 12 to 18 months.</p>
<p>Goldman Sachs recommends that investors allocate 25 percent of their assets to bonds in their global portfolios, against the usual level of between 20 percent and 40 percent, he said.</p>
<p>Goldman's recommended allocation for equities is 57 percent, against a usual level of between 45 percent and 65 percent, he told a seminar.</p>
<p>&quot;We like equities, in particular European (ones),&quot; he said.</p>
<p>Although stock prices have been rising sharply over the past few years, there is no serious danger of them overshooting in a period of easy monetary policy, he said.</p>
<p>Meanwhile, Weingarten said Goldman had selected a list of the best 30 stocks in world stock markets, whose growth ratio is much bigger than the market average and whose price earnings ratio is just above the markets' average.</p>
<p>These include Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp, Sony Corp and Sumitomo Electric Industries Ltd, he said.</p>
<p>The others are AFLAC Inc, AlliedSignal Inc, Cadence Design Systems Inc, Citicorp, El Paso Energy Corp, Fluor Corp, Intel Corp, MBNA Corp, MGIC Investment Corp, Philip Morris, Safeway Inc and Estee Lauder Cos.</p>
<p>Also among the 30 issues were Bass, B.A.T. Industries, Ericsson, HSBC, Novartis, Roche, Sema, Unilever Plc, VEBA, Zurich Insurance, Hutchison Whampoa, National Mutual Asia, PTT Exploration and Production Plc, United Overseas Bank and BANACCI.</p>
